<subSubSection pageId="58" pageNumber="59" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="58.[151,1436,1801,2006]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,266,1801,1826]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. A dark gray butterfly with no forewing ocelli, and extremely aberrant wing venation. Forewing R 
<number box="[1381,1391,1802,1826]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" value="1.0">1</number>
has a separate origin at the anterior end of the discal cell and fuses with the subcosta, while the remaining radial veins branch as follows; R 
<number box="[385,399,1873,1898]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" value="5.0">5</number>
, R 
<number box="[430,444,1874,1898]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" value="2.0">2</number>
, R 
<number box="[477,489,1874,1898]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" value="3.0">3</number>
+R 
<number box="[526,541,1874,1898]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" value="4.0">4</number>
. in the hindwing, vein A 
<number box="[819,831,1874,1898]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" value="3.0">3</number>
is absent.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="59" lastPageNumber="60" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="58.[151,1436,1801,2006]" lastBlockId="59.[151,1436,151,429]" lastPageId="59" lastPageNumber="60" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1909,1934]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Remarks</emphasis>
. In the original description, Heimlich associated 
<taxonomicName box="[884,1116,1910,1933]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Pamperis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="poaoeneis">
<emphasis box="[884,1116,1910,1933]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Pamperis poaoeneis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with 
<taxonomicName box="[1187,1345,1910,1933]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Cosmosatyrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1187,1345,1910,1933]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Cosmosatyrus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but he considered the resemblance insufficient for placing in that genus, and created the monotypic genus 
<taxonomicName box="[1287,1395,1946,1969]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Pamperis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1287,1395,1946,1969]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Pamperis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for this unusual species based primarily on peculiarities in the wing venation. 
<bibRefCitation author="Miller" box="[1032,1188,1981,2006]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" refString="Miller, L. D. (1968) The higher classification, phylogeny and zoogeography of the Satyridae (Lepidoptera). Memoirs of the American Entomological Society, 24, 1 - 174. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1130 / MEM 110 - p 1" type="journal article" year="1968">
Miller (
<number box="[1121,1179,1981,2006]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" value="1968.0">1968</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
further set 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Pamperis" kingdom="Animalia" lastPageId="59" lastPageNumber="60" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="poaoeneis">
<emphasis italics="true" lastPageId="59" lastPageNumber="60" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Pamperis poaoeneis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
apart as a genus of uncertain position, again due to its unusual venation, noting that &quot;the veins in the apical portion of the forewing are arranged like no known satyrid.&quot; 
<bibRefCitation author="Pyrcz" box="[965,1275,188,213]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" refString="Pyrcz, T. W. &amp; Wojtusiak, J. (2010) A new species of Argyrophorus Blanchard from northern Peru and considerations on the value of wing venation as a source of synapomorphies in some temperate Neotropical Satyrinae (Lepidoptera: Nymphalidae). Genus, 21, 605 - 613." type="journal article" year="2010">
Pyrcz &amp; Wojtusiak (
<number box="[1208,1267,188,212]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" value="2010.0">2010</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
synonymized 
<taxonomicName box="[151,259,225,248]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Pamperis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,259,225,248]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Pamperis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with 
<taxonomicName box="[325,480,223,248]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Argyrophorus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[325,480,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Argyrophorus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but noted its unusual venation, the absence of an M 
<number box="[1086,1095,224,248]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" value="1.0">1</number>
-M 
<number box="[1131,1146,224,248]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" value="2.0">2</number>
ventral forewing ocellus, and antennae only partially covered in scales as features that set it apart: in other words, it is very little like 
<taxonomicName box="[151,306,295,320]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Argyrophorus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,306,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Argyrophorus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
at all. 
<bibRefCitation author="Miller" box="[396,552,295,320]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" refString="Miller, L. D. (1968) The higher classification, phylogeny and zoogeography of the Satyridae (Lepidoptera). Memoirs of the American Entomological Society, 24, 1 - 174. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1130 / MEM 110 - p 1" type="journal article" year="1968">
Miller (
<number box="[485,543,295,320]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" value="1968.0">1968</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
also noted, &quot;Until these structures, as well as others not considered in the original description, have been studied, it will be quite impossible to assign this genus to its proper position among the 
<taxonomicName box="[198,310,367,392]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Satyridae</taxonomicName>
.&quot; Molecular data confirm what morphology suggests: that 
<taxonomicName box="[1009,1243,369,392]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Pamperis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="poaoeneis">
<emphasis box="[1009,1243,369,392]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Pamperis poaoeneis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinct from 
<taxonomicName box="[151,306,404,429]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Argyrophorus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,306,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Argyrophorus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or any other taxon. 
<taxonomicName box="[531,638,405,428]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Pamperis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[531,638,405,428]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Pamperis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, then, remains a valid monotypic genus.
</paragraph>
